<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="40" type="n.">
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="40">N.B.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="40">
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Cuspidariidae" genus="Cuspidaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cuspidaria cochinensis" order="Lamiales" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="cochinensis">Cuspidaria cochinensis</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 12
<normalizedToken originalValue="a–c">a-c</normalizedToken>
) was transferred from the 
<taxonomicName family="Cuspidariidae" lsidName="" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" rank="family">Cuspidariidae</taxonomicName>
into the corbulid genus 
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Corbulidae" genus="Cuneocorbula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cuneocorbula" order="Myida" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Cuneocorbula</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation pageId="19" pageNumber="40">Oliver et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
. Besides its extremely corbulid-like shell, the hinge is reminiscent of that of corbulids in which there is a relatively prominent tooth in the right valve. However, following this review, this tooth is no longer regarded as equivalent to the large anterior tooth possessed by 
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Corbulidae" genus="Potamocorbula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Potamocorbula" order="Myida" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Potamocorbula</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Corbulidae" genus="Lentidium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lentidium" order="Myida" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Lentidium</taxonomicName>
. The tooth in 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. cochinensis" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" rank="species" species="cochinensis">C. cochinensis</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 7o) is a thickening of the hinge margin and thus structurally identical to the pseudo tooth seen in 
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Myidae" genus="Mya" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mya" order="Myida" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Mya</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Myidae" genus="Sphenia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sphenia" order="Myida" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Sphenia</taxonomicName>
. The chondrophore of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. cochinensis" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" rank="species" species="cochinensis">C. cochinensis</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 7n) has a posterior flange and this too is identical to the form seen in 
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Myidae" genus="Sphenia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sphenia" order="Myida" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Sphenia</taxonomicName>
. Consequently, we transfer 
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Corbulidae" genus="Cuneocorbula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cuneocorbula cochinensis" order="Myida" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="cochinensis">Cuneocorbula cochinensis</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Myidae" genus="Indosphenia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Indosphenia" order="Myida" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Indosphenia</taxonomicName>
in the 
<taxonomicName family="Myidae" lsidName="" pageId="19" pageNumber="40" rank="family">Myidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
